1
00:00:00,318 --> 00:00:26,038
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:26,574 --> 00:00:31,199
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:35,685 --> 00:00:39,069
Put my microphone on.

4
00:00:39,088 --> 00:00:39,389
Okay.

5
00:00:40,270 --> 00:00:49,299
So I thought today we'd tackle a more, a slightly more, for want of a better word, mystical discourse.

6
00:00:49,399 --> 00:00:55,265
And it's called, or it's called after, somebody called Bahia of the Barcloth.

7
00:00:55,634 --> 00:01:09,897
now um whenever you get people writing about saints and um and holy people hagiography they always of course pump it up to make sure that either the person is amazing or the teacher

8
00:01:10,534 --> 00:01:18,903
Now, it's not that the Buddha wasn't an amazing teacher, but in order to make him more amazing, we got this story about Bahia.

9
00:01:19,245 --> 00:01:23,608
So he was a merchant and he used to ply up and down the Indian coast.

10
00:01:24,370 --> 00:01:28,575
And one day he was shipwrecked and on a raft he made land.

11
00:01:29,195 --> 00:01:31,317
And suddenly he starts wearing a bark cloth.

12
00:01:31,817 --> 00:01:40,507
Now, for those of you who want to know what a bark cloth is, you have to peel the inner bark off trees and beat it until it's soft.

13
00:01:40,876 --> 00:01:48,061
And then it can be used as a loincloth, skirt, draperies and wall hangings and in thick layers make an excellent bed.

14
00:01:48,882 --> 00:01:50,164
So that's what you can do tomorrow.

15
00:01:51,125 --> 00:01:57,950
But it also says it's an ancient art which is deeply involved in religious and ceremonial life.

16
00:01:57,990 --> 00:01:58,831
So remember that bit.

17
00:02:00,313 --> 00:02:04,957
Anyway, he starts wearing this bark cloth and he becomes a mendicant.

18
00:02:05,117 --> 00:02:06,338
And of course, people feed him.

19
00:02:06,358 --> 00:02:10,883
And after a while, he got the impression that, in fact, he was fully liberated.

20
00:02:11,706 --> 00:02:24,846
Well, as these stories go, a god appeared to him, an old relation, and said to him, no, you're not liberated, you're not enlightened.

21
00:02:24,925 --> 00:02:27,930
In fact, spiritually speaking, you're as thick as a plank.

22
00:02:28,670 --> 00:02:31,354
And the person you want to go and meet is the Buddha.

23
00:02:32,015 --> 00:02:34,278
So, of course, off he goes to meet the Buddha.

24
00:02:34,419 --> 00:02:37,443
He must have been a bit disappointed at that revelation, mind, you know.

25
00:02:40,056 --> 00:02:43,263
Now, when he gets to the Buddha, of course, we'll come to that.

26
00:02:43,944 --> 00:03:02,841
So I think a better story, shall we say, which seems more true, is that the Brahmins were, of course, developing their own scriptures, which were called the Upanishads, translates as sort of connection, but also known as the Vedanta, the end of the Vedas.

27
00:03:02,820 --> 00:03:14,219
And they were specifically interested in who we were, what was the ground of our being, right?

28
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:15,040
Ontology.

29
00:03:16,082 --> 00:03:29,604
So, this is a passage from the Bhadranya Upanishad, and this is what it says.

30
00:03:32,520 --> 00:03:46,657
That imperishable is the unseen seer, the unheard hearer, the unthought thinker, the un-understood understander.

31
00:03:47,997 --> 00:04:01,633
Other than it there is naught that sees, other than it there is naught that hears, other than it there is naught that thinks, and other than it there is naught that understands.

32
00:04:02,169 --> 00:04:07,676
In other words, it's pointing to this self, which is transcendent of everything.

33
00:04:08,578 --> 00:04:11,882
But it's interesting to see how it is expressed.

34
00:04:12,262 --> 00:04:18,589
The imperishable, that which does not change, etc., etc., is the unseen seer.

35
00:04:19,471 --> 00:04:20,812
The unseen seer.

36
00:04:20,833 --> 00:04:22,113
Okay.

37
00:04:22,134 --> 00:04:26,660
So it's very Zen, you know, like the effortless effort, the unseen seer.

38
00:04:27,882 --> 00:04:28,262
Okay.

39
00:04:29,692 --> 00:04:36,942
Now, these people who followed this particular Upanishad used to wear the bark cloth.

40
00:04:36,983 --> 00:04:44,072
That was their signature dress, just like the Buddhist monks went around with a bald head.

41
00:04:44,512 --> 00:04:50,781
Everybody else had long matted hair, dreadlocks, but the Buddha made us shave our heads.

42
00:04:52,742 --> 00:04:59,312
So all these sects had their own little way of manifesting who or what they were following.

43
00:05:00,726 --> 00:05:06,336
So he's obviously heard about the Buddha, and he comes to find him.

44
00:05:07,297 --> 00:05:13,567
And he finds him on alms round, and the Buddha says, you know, this isn't the time.

45
00:05:13,627 --> 00:05:21,158
And he says, look, I'm a very old man, and you're not so young, and we could die any moment.

46
00:05:21,298 --> 00:05:23,642
So really, you know, please give me the teaching.

47
00:05:23,862 --> 00:05:26,127
So the Buddha, out of his compassion, does so.

48
00:05:27,035 --> 00:05:38,026
And now as the story goes, not long after he was fully liberated, he got gored by a cow who was looking after her calf, right?

49
00:05:38,646 --> 00:05:41,110
So again, I think we can take that with a little pinch of salt.

50
00:05:42,670 --> 00:05:53,262
Anyway, this is what the Buddha says to him.

51
00:05:54,052 --> 00:05:57,675
Here in Bahia you should train yourself thus.

52
00:05:58,776 --> 00:06:01,559
In the seen there is merely the seen.

53
00:06:01,598 --> 00:06:06,403
In the heard there is merely what is heard.

54
00:06:06,983 --> 00:06:11,468
And in the sensed there is merely what is sensed.

55
00:06:11,487 --> 00:06:15,732
In the cognized there is merely what is cognized.

56
00:06:15,752 --> 00:06:18,274
And in this way you should train yourself, Bahia.

57
00:06:19,095 --> 00:06:22,978
Now, if you're listening to this, you may very well become fully liberated.

58
00:06:24,848 --> 00:06:29,012
Here's the crucial bit.

59
00:06:29,033 --> 00:06:52,999
When Bahía, for you, in the seen there is merely what is seen, in the heard merely what is heard, in the sensed merely what is sensed, and in the cognized is merely what is cognized, then, Bahía, you will not be with that.

60
00:06:53,653 --> 00:07:21,720
when by here you are not with that then by here you will not be in that and when by here you are not in that then by here you will neither be here nor beyond nor in between the two just this is the end of suffering anybody awaken no don't worry it didn't work for me either

61
00:07:24,687 --> 00:07:26,910
So now, what's the Buddha saying here?

62
00:07:29,213 --> 00:07:30,394
Let me just go back up a bit.

63
00:07:30,535 --> 00:07:31,076
Yes, that's right.

64
00:07:31,357 --> 00:07:32,639
What's the Buddha saying here?

65
00:07:32,658 --> 00:07:49,041
So, in Buddhist psychology, we have a sense base, we have something that the sense base is aware of, or senses, rather, senses, and there is the awareness, the consciousness.

66
00:07:49,262 --> 00:07:51,605
This consciousness is dependent

67
00:07:52,783 --> 00:07:53,725
on the sense base.

68
00:07:53,946 --> 00:07:59,475
So that's why the Buddha enumerates consciousnesses according to the sense basis.

69
00:07:59,836 --> 00:08:05,485
So you have eye consciousness, nose consciousness, ear consciousness, etc., etc.

70
00:08:07,108 --> 00:08:09,492
So here what the Buddha is saying is

71
00:08:09,894 --> 00:08:12,877
that in any given experience there's an object.

72
00:08:13,017 --> 00:08:17,541
It could be a video you're watching, it could be a biscuit you're eating, whatever.

73
00:08:17,581 --> 00:08:18,622
That's the object.

74
00:08:19,163 --> 00:08:21,725
And he's saying when you are not with that.

75
00:08:22,786 --> 00:08:26,151
So that's a connection of being with something.

76
00:08:27,851 --> 00:08:37,961
And when you're not with that, then the sense base, if you're not aware of something through a sense base, then you're not in the sense base.

77
00:08:38,514 --> 00:08:43,221
And if you're not in the sense base, then consciousness cannot arise.

78
00:08:45,183 --> 00:09:07,273
So you're neither there with the object, here with the sense base, and in between with that consciousness, which is a screen upon which these two things arise.

79
00:09:09,008 --> 00:09:20,577
When you experience something beyond that, then you've experienced something which is not part of the psycho-physical organism.

80
00:09:21,619 --> 00:09:24,381
And just this is the awakening.

81
00:09:36,432 --> 00:09:36,653
Yeah?

82
00:09:40,244 --> 00:09:42,412
Now, this is recorded, so I'm not going to repeat it.

83
00:09:43,033 --> 00:09:47,289
I couldn't repeat it anyway, but you've got the idea anyway.

84
00:09:47,309 --> 00:09:49,056
So you can always listen to it again if you want.

85
00:09:51,448 --> 00:09:56,336
Now, the thing is that when Bahiyya hears this, he is actually immediately enlightened.

86
00:09:56,576 --> 00:09:58,919
And the Buddha actually gives him a title.

87
00:09:59,240 --> 00:10:02,666
He gave titles to certain disciples who had special gifts.

88
00:10:03,086 --> 00:10:15,104
So, for instance, Sariputta was called the Dhammasanapati, the general of the Dharma, because of his understanding of the Dharma, which was said to be second only to the Buddha.

89
00:10:15,124 --> 00:10:18,469
So he called him, wait till I find it, where are we?

90
00:10:22,094 --> 00:10:24,177
I'm moving around too much on this page.

91
00:10:29,385 --> 00:10:42,066
Pipabina Thicham, the quickest person to become liberated amongst all those who were quick to become liberated.

92
00:10:42,787 --> 00:10:45,672
That's the title he gave him.

93
00:10:48,993 --> 00:10:55,039
And as I say, later on, as it's said, he dies from an attack from a cow.

94
00:10:55,941 --> 00:11:04,610
So now this is the story of Bahir of the Barcloth, and it fits into the Udana Sutta.

95
00:11:04,730 --> 00:11:09,215
So these are a collection of the inspired verses of the Buddha.

96
00:11:09,975 --> 00:11:18,105
And next week, I'll actually read that discourse and the Buddha's own response in verse, which will add to this meaning.

97
00:11:20,717 --> 00:11:22,539
as if I explain it correctly.

98
00:11:24,982 --> 00:11:46,370
So I hope that has been of some use, that it has not confused you, and that by your insight meditation, by seeing this process of how we create the world, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

